# C++ Coding Standards (Boyle)

## 1. Baseline Style

- **C++23** with **GNU extensions** where needed for performance or toolchain compatibility.
- **clang-format**: Microsoft base style (see `.clang-format`). Do not fight the formatter except for documented `clang-format off` blocks when unavoidable.
- **No** Google C++ Style Guide as authority—use Boyle rules and `.github/instructions/cpp-coding-standards.instructions.md`.

## 2. Trailing Return Types

**MANDATORY** for new and updated functions:

```cpp
auto euclidean(Vec2d a, Vec2d b) noexcept -> double;
```

Exception: constructors, destructors, and operators where the project already uses a consistent alternate style—stay consistent within a file.

## 3. Naming

| Element | Convention | Example |
| ------- | ---------- | ------- |
| Namespace | `snake_case` | `boyle::math` |
| Class / struct | `PascalCase` | `CooMatrix` |
| Function / method | `camelCase` | `updateCoeff` |
| Public data members | `snake_case` | `row_ptr` |
| Private members | `m_` prefix | `m_data` |
| Constants | `kPascalCase` | `kEpsilon` |
| Concepts | `PascalCase` | `ScalarArithmetic` |
| Macros | `BOYLE_UPPER_SNAKE` | `BOYLE_CHECK_PARAMS` |

## 4. Headers and Includes

- **`#pragma once`** for include guards.
- **Include order**: C/C++ standard library → third-party → `boyle/...`, groups separated by blank lines; alphabetical within groups when practical.
- **Include what you use**; do not rely on transitive includes.
- Prefer **nested namespace** syntax: `namespace boyle::math { ... }`.
- **Never** `using namespace` in headers. In `.cpp`, avoid `using namespace` at global scope.

## 5. Class Design

- **`final`** on classes not designed for inheritance.
- **`explicit`** on single-argument constructors unless implicit conversion is intentional and documented.
- **`override`** on all virtual overrides; **`virtual` destructor** when polymorphic.
- Prefer **`struct`** for passive aggregates; **`class`** when enforcing invariants.
- Use macros from `boyle/common/utils/macros.hpp` for copy/move control (`ENABLE_COPY`, `DISABLE_COPY`, etc.).

## 6. GNU Attributes (hot paths)

Use judiciously on proven hot paths:

```cpp
[[using gnu: always_inline]]
[[using gnu: pure, always_inline]]
[[using gnu: const, always_inline, leaf]]
[[using gnu: always_inline, leaf, hot]]
```

## 7. `constexpr` and `noexcept`

- Mark functions **`constexpr`** when they can be; use **`noexcept`** when failure is not part of the contract.
- Parameter-checked accessors often use: `noexcept(!BOYLE_CHECK_PARAMS)` or equivalent—follow existing patterns in the type.

## 8. Error Handling

- Use **exceptions** (`std::invalid_argument`, `std::out_of_range`, etc.) for unrecoverable misuse.
- **`BOYLE_CHECK_PARAMS`**: when enabled, validate preconditions and throw or assert per existing module style—**do not** introduce alternative status-channel types.

## 9. Concepts and Templates

- Constrain templates with **concepts** and meaningful names (`Scalar`, `Index`, ...).
- Prefer **requires** clauses or `static_assert` with clear messages for template diagnostics.

## 10. BLAS / LAPACK

- Call the configured **BLAS/LAPACK** (e.g. OpenBLAS); do not reimplement matrix multiply or dense factorization unless explicitly scoped as experimental research code.

## 11. Namespaces

- Never **`using namespace std`** or **`using namespace boyle`** in headers.
- Close namespaces with an end comment: `} // namespace boyle::math`.

## 12. Comments

- **File-level**: Doxygen `@file`, `@brief`, `@copyright` (see `basic/copyright.mdc`).
- Avoid repeating obvious behavior in line comments; document invariants, units, and non-obvious numerics.

## 13. Serialization

- Use **Boost.Serialization** where the project already serializes types; add **roundtrip tests** (see `cpp-testing-guidelines.mdc`).

## 14. Formatting Nuances

- Floating literals: include digits on both sides of the decimal (`1.0`, not `1.`).
- Prefer **trailing return type** consistently for free functions and member functions.

## 15. `auto` Rules

- Use `auto` when the type is clear from the right-hand side (`make_unique`, `static_cast`, iterators).
- Use **`auto&`** or **`const auto&`** when the initializer is a reference to avoid copies.
- Range-for: `for (const auto& x : items)`.

## 16. Lambdas

- Keep lambdas **short**; use named functions for multi-step logic.
- **Avoid** default captures `[=]` / `[&]`; capture explicitly.
- Be careful capturing **`this`**; prefer pointers or refs with clear lifetime.

## 17. `switch` and Casts

- Prefer **`std::visit`** on `std::variant` where appropriate; otherwise `switch` with **`default`** for non-enumerated values.
- Use **`static_cast`**, **`reinterpret_cast`**, **`const_cast`**—never C-style casts.
- Annotate intentional fall-through with **`[[fallthrough]]`**.

## 18. `std::span` and `std::string_view`

- Use **`std::span<const T>`** / **`std::span<T>`** instead of pointer + length for buffers.
- Use **`std::string_view`** for read-only string parameters; **do not store** `string_view` in owning objects unless lifetime is guaranteed.

## 19. Designated Initializers

- Use **designated initializers** for aggregates when readability improves; field order must match the type definition.

## 20. Type Aliases

- Prefer **`using`** over `typedef`.
- Template aliases: `template <class T> using Vec3 = ...`.
- Scalar variants use **`s` / `d` / `c` / `z`** suffixes consistently.

## 21. Move Semantics

- Move when transferring ownership; mark move operations `noexcept` when appropriate for STL compatibility.
